==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Worthy
<hw>Wor"thy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Worthier</adjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Worthiest.</adjf>]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>worthi</ets>,
<ets>wur⟦thorn⟧i</ets>, from <ets>worth</ets>, <ets>wur⟦thorn⟧</ets>,
n.; cf. Icel. <ets>ver⟦edh⟧ugr</ets>, D. <ets>waardig</ets>, G.
<ets>w⟦uum⟧rdig</ets>, OHG. <ets>wird⟦imac⟧g</ets>. See <er>Worth</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having worth or excellence; possessing merit;
valuable; deserving; estimable; excellent; virtuous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full <qex>worthy</qex> was he in his lordes war.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These banished men that I have kept withal⟦br⟧
Are men endued with <qex>worthy</qex> qualities.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Happier thou mayst be, <qex>worthier</qex> canst not be.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>worthy</qex> mind should <qex>worthy</qex> things
embrace.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having suitable, adapted, or equivalent qualities or
value; -- usually with <xex>of</xex> before the thing compared or the
object; more rarely, with a following infinitive instead of
<xex>of</xex>, or with <xex>that</xex>; <as>as, <ex>worthy</ex> of,
equal in excellence, value, or dignity to</as>; entitled to; meriting;
-- usually in a good sense, but sometimes in a bad one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No, Warwick, thou art <qex>worthy</qex> of the sway.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The merciless Macdonwald,⟦br⟧
<qex>Worthy</qex> to be a rebel.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose shoes I am not <qex>worthy</qex> to bear.</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
iii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And thou art <qex>worthy</qex> that thou shouldst not know⟦br⟧
More happiness.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lodging is well <qex>worthy</qex> of the guest.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of high station; of high social position.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Worthy</qex> women of the town.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Worthiest of blood</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law of
Descent)</fld>, <cd>most worthy of those of the same blood to succeed or
inherit; -- applied to males, and expressive of the preference given
them over females.</cd> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worthy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Worthy
<hw>Wor"thy</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Worthies</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>A man of eminent worth or value; one
distinguished for useful and estimable qualities; a person of
conspicuous desert; -- much used in the plural; <as>as, the
<ex>worthies</ex> of the church; political <ex>worthies</ex>; military
<ex>worthies</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blood of ancient <qex>worthies</qex> in his veins.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Worthy</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Worthy
<hw>Wor"thy</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To render worthy; to exalt into
a hero.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wost</ent>⟦br⟧
